UtHnh0aHaa	Communication is not just the complexities of language and verbal exchange. Clarity is often difficult to establish unless you know the method.<br>  <br>  For example, a statement of confidence can be exuded by physical upright posture or appropriate clothing for the occasion.<br>  <br>  Very often, a wise nod of acknowledgment is far more effective to show empathy when engaged in a verbal conversation. Body language and eye movements can indicate interest and sincerity. Walk ten percent faster to show enthusiasm.<br>  <br>  With regard to verbal exchange, the old adage 'we were given 2 ears and only one mouth so we can listen twice as much as we talk' is an exercise in social posturing. One appears wise when the sit back and listen with only acknowledgments when appropriate.<br>  <br>  Be creative in your scrapbook to get these points across clearly and you will have a winning project.|`|26DoxkOBaa	I do what is called a "two-way communication cycle." It starts when I or someone else says something to me, and I reply with an acknowledgment that I got what he said, like OK, and then I say something back. The person that started the communication should acknowledge my communication by saying something to let me know that he understood what I said, and then might say something back to me.<br>  <br>  What's important is letting the person know that you understood what they said. And if the conversation is one-sided, then the other person might lose interest and stop talking. <br>  <br>  Understanding comes in three parts. Communication (words), Reality (both of you agreeing about something) and affinity (liking the other person enough to communicate with them. When you have all three going it leads to understanding. If you want, lets say, more affinity from someone, you talk to them and agree with something about them. Those two things raises the other third side, which is affinity.<br>  <br>  Hope this helps you.
